column2: select t1.id, t1.maker from car_makers as t1 join model_list as t2 on t1.id = t2.maker group by t1.id having count(*) >= 2
column3: car_1 | select t1.id, t1.maker from car_makers as t1 join model_list as t2 on t1.id = t2.maker group by t1.id having count(*) >= 2 intersect select t1.id, t1.maker from car_makers as t1 join model_list as t2 on t1.id = t2.maker join car_names as t3 on t2.model = t3.model group by t1.id having count(*) > 3;

column1: What are the id and names of the countries which have more than 3 car makers or produce the 'fiat' model?
column2: select t1.countryid, t1.countryname from countries as t1 join car_makers as t2 on t1.countryid = t2.country where t2.maker = "fiat" group by t1.countryid having count(*) > 3 union select t1.countryid, t1.countryname from countries as t1 join model_list as t2 on t1.countryid = t2.modelid where t2.model = "fiat"
column3: car_1 | select t1.countryid, t1.countryname from countries as t1 join car_makers as t2 on t1.countryid = t2.country group by t1.countryid having count(*) > 3 union select t1.countryid, t1.countryname from countries as t1 join car_makers as t2 on t1.countryid = t2.country join model_list as t3 on t2.id = t3.maker where t3.model = 'fiat';

column1: What are the ids and names of all countries that either have more than 3 car makers or produce fiat model ?
column2: select t1.countryid, t1.countryname from countries as t1 join car_makers as t2 on t1.countryid = t2.country where t2.maker = "Fiat" group by t1.countryid having count(*) > 3 union select t1.countryid, t1.countryname from countries as t1 join model_list as t2 on t1.countryid = t2.modelid where t2.maker = "Fiat"
column3: car_1 | select t1.countryid, t1.countryname from countries as t1 join car_makers as t2 on t1.countryid = t2.country group by t1.countryid having count(*) > 3 union select t1.countryid, t1.countryname from countries as t1 join car_makers as t2 on t1.countryid = t2.country join model_list as t3 on t2.id = t3.maker where t3.model = 'fiat';

column1: How many 'United Airlines' flights go to Airport 'ASY'?
column2: select count(*) from airlines as t1 join flights as t2 on t1.uid = t2.airline where t1.airline = 'United Airlines' and t2.airportcode
column3: flight_2 | select count(*) from airlines as t1 join flights as t2 on t2.airline = t1.uid where t1.airline = "United Airlines" and t2.destairport = "ASY"

column1: Count the number of United Airlines flights arriving in ASY Airport.
column2: select count(*) from airlines as t1 join flights as t2 on t1.uid = t2.airline where t1.airline = 'United Airlines' and t2.airportcode
column3: flight_2 | select count(*) from airlines as t1 join flights as t2 on t2.airline = t1.uid where t1.airline = "United Airlines" and t2.destairport = "ASY"

column1: How many United Airlines flights go to City 'Aberdeen'?
column2: select count(*) from airlines as t1 join flights as t2 on t1.uid = t2.airline join airports as t3 on t2.airportcode
column3: flight_2 | select count(*) from flights as t1 join airports as t2 on t1.destairport = t2.airportcode join airlines as t3 on t3.uid = t1.airline where t2.city = "Aberdeen" and t3.airline = "United Airlines"

column1: Which airline has most number of flights?
column2: select t1.airline from airlines as t1 join flights as t2 on t1.uid = t2.airline group by t2.airline order by count(*) desc limit 1
column3: flight_2 | select t1.airline from airlines as t1 join flights as t2 on t1.uid = t2.airline group by t1.airline order by count(*) desc limit 1

column1: What airline serves the most flights?
column2: select t1.airline from airlines as t1 join flights as t2 on t1.uid = t2.airline group by t2.airline order by count(*) desc limit 1
column3: flight_2 | select t1.airline from airlines as t1 join flights as t2 on t1.uid = t2.airline group by t1.airline order by count(*) desc limit 1

column1: Find the abbreviation and country of the airline that has fewest number of flights?
column2: select t1.abbreviation, t1.country from airlines as t1 join flights as t2 on t1.uid = t2.airline group by t2.airline order by count(*) limit 1
column3: flight_2 | select t1.abbreviation, t1.country from airlines as t1 join flights as t2 on t1.uid = t2.airline group by t1.airline order by count(*) limit 1

column1: What is the abbreviation of the airilne has the fewest flights and what country is it in?
column2: select t1.abbreviation, t1.country from airlines as t1 join flights as t2 on t1.uid = t2.sourceairport group by t2.sourceairport order by count(*) limit 1
column3: flight_2 | select t1.abbreviation, t1.country from airlines as t1 join flights as t2 on t1.uid = t2.airline group by t1.airline order by count(*) limit 1

column1: Find all airlines that have fewer than 200 flights.
column2: select airline from flights group by airline having count(*) < 200
column3: flight_2 | select t1.airline from airlines as t1 join flights as t2 on t1.uid = t2.airline group by t1.airline having count(*) < 200

column1: Find the name of airports which do not have any flight in and out.
column2: select airportname from airports where airportcode not in (select sourceairport, destairport from flights)
column3: flight_2 | select airportname from airports where airportcode not in (select sourceairport from flights union select destairport from flights)

column1: Which airports do not have departing or arriving flights?
column2: select airportname from airports except select t1.airportname from airports as t1 join flights as t2 on t1.airportcode = t2.destairport
column3: flight_2 | select airportname from airports where airportcode not in (select sourceairport from flights union select destairport from flights)

column3: course_teach | select name from teacher where hometown!= "little lever urban district"

column1: What are the id, name and membership level of visitors who have spent the largest amount of money in total in all museum tickets?
column2: select t1.id, t1.name, t1.level_of_membership from visitor as t1 join visit as t2 on t1.id = t2.visitor_id group by t1.id order by sum(total_spent) desc limit 1
column3: museum_visit | select t2.visitor_id, t1.name, t1.level_of_membership from visitor as t1 join visit as t2 on t1.id = t2.visitor_id group by t2.visitor_id order by sum(t2.total_spent) desc limit 1

column1: What are the country code and first name of the players who won in both tourney WTA Championships and Australian Open?
column2: select t1.country_code, t1.first_name from players as t1 join matches as t2 on t1.player_id = t2.winner_id where t2.tourney_name = "WTA Championships" intersect select t1.country_code, t1.first_name from players as t1 join matches as t2 on t1.player_id = t2.winner_id where t2.t
column3: wta_1 | select t1.country_code, t1.first_name from players as t1 join matches as t2 on t1.player_id = t2.winner_id where t2.tourney_name = 'WTA Championships' intersect select t1.country_code, t1.first_name from players as t1 join matches as t2 on t1.player_id = t2.winner_id where t2.tourney_name = 'Australian Open'

column1: What are the first names and country codes for players who won both the WTA Championships and the Australian Open?

column3: wta_1 | select t1.country_code, t1.first_name from players as t1 join matches as t2 on t1.player_id = t2.winner_id where t2.tourney_name = 'WTA Championships' intersect select t1.country_code, t1.first_name from players as t1 join matches as t2 on t1.player_id = t2.winner_id where t2.tourney_name = 'Australian Open'

column3: wta_1 | select t1.country_code, t1.first_name from players as t1 join rankings as t2 on t1.player_id = t2.player_id order by t2.tours desc limit 1

column3: wta_1 | select winner_name, winner_rank_points from matches group by winner_name order by count(*) desc limit 1

column3: wta_1 | select winner_name, loser_name from matches order by minutes desc limit 1

column3: wta_1 | select avg(ranking), t1.first_name from players as t1 join rankings as t2 on t1.player_id = t2.player_id group by t1.first_name

column1: Find the total ranking points for each player and their first name.

column3: wta_1 | select sum(ranking_points), t1.first_name from players as t1 join rankings as t2 on t1.player_id = t2.player_id group by t1.first_name

column1: Find the number of left handed winners who participated in the WTA Championships.

column1: List the name, date and result of each battle.
column2: select name, date, result from battle
column3: battle_death | select name, date from battle

column1: What is maximum and minimum death toll caused each time?
column2: select max(killed), min(killed), t1.id from death as t1 join battle as t2 on t1.id = t2.id group by t1.id
column3: battle_death | select max(killed), min(killed) from death

column1: What are the different ids and names of the battles that lost any 'Brig' type shipes?
column2: select distinct t1.id, t1.name from battle as t1 join ship as t2 on t1.id = t2.id where t2.ship_type = 'Brig'
column3: battle_death | select distinct t1.id, t1.name from battle as t1 join ship as t2 on t1.id = t2.lost_in_battle where t2.ship_type = 'Brig'

column1: What are the ids and names of the battles that led to more than 10 people killed in total.
column2: select t1.id, t1.name from battle as t1 join death as t2 on t1.id = t2.caused_by_ship_id group by t1.id having sum(t2.killed) > 10
column3: battle_death | select t1.id, t1.name from battle as t1 join ship as t2 on t1.id = t2.lost_in_battle join death as t3 on t2.id = t3.caused_by_ship_id group by t1.id having sum(t3.killed) > 10

column1: What is the ship id and name that caused most total injuries?
column2: select t1.id, t1.name from ship as t1 join death as t2 on t1.id = t2.caused_by_ship_id group by t1.id order by sum(injured) desc limit 1
column3: battle_death | select t2.id, t2.name from death as t1 join ship as t2 on t1.caused_by_ship_id = t2.id group by t2.id order by count(*) desc limit 1

column1: what are all the addresses including line 1 and line 2?
column2: select address_id from addresses where address_id like "%line_1%" intersect select address_id from addresses where address_id like "%line_2%"
column3: student_transcripts_tracking | select line_1, line_2 from addresses

column1: What are the names and ids of every course with less than 2 sections?
column2: select t1.course_name, t2.course_id from courses as t1 join sections as t2 on t1.course_id = t2.course_id group by t2.course_id having count(*) < 2
column3: student_transcripts_tracking | select t1.course_name, t1.course_id from courses as t1 join sections as t2 on t1.course_id = t2.course_id group by t1.course_id having count(*) <= 2

column1: Who are enrolled in 2 degree programs in one semester? List the first name, middle name and last name and the id.
column2: select t2.first_name, t2.middle_name, t2.last_name, t1.student_enrolment_id from student_enrolment as t1 join students as t2 on t1.student_id = t2.student_id group by t1.student_enrolment_id having count(*) = 2
column3: student_transcripts_tracking | select t1.first_name, t1.middle_name, t1.last_name, t1.student_id from students as t1 join student_enrolment as t2 on t1.student_id = t2.student_id group by t1.student_id having count(*) = 2

column1: What are the first, middle, and last names for everybody enrolled in a Bachelors program?
column2: select t2.first_name, t2.middle_name, t2.last_name from student_enrolment as t1 join students as t2 on t1.student_id = t2.student_id where t1.degree_program_id = 'Bachelors'
column3: student_transcripts_tracking | select distinct t1.first_name, t1.middle_name, t1.last_name from students as t1 join student_enrolment as t2 on t1.student_id = t2.student_id join degree_programs as t3 on t2.degree_program_id = t3.degree_program_id where t3.degree_summary_name = 'Bachelor'

column1: Find the kind of program which most number of students are enrolled in?

column3: student_transcripts_tracking | select t1.degree_summary_name from degree_programs as t1 join student_enrolment as t2 on t1.degree_program_id = t2.degree_program_id group by t1.degree_summary_name order by count(*) desc limit 1

column1: Find the program which most number of students are enrolled in. List both the id and the summary.

column3: student_transcripts_tracking | select t1.degree_program_id, t1.degree_summary_name from degree_programs as t1 join student_enrolment as t2 on t1.degree_program_id = t2.degree_program_id group by t1.degree_program_id order by count(*) desc limit 1

column1: What is the program id and the summary of the degree that has the most students enrolled?

column3: student_transcripts_tracking | select t1.degree_program_id, t1.degree_summary_name from degree_programs as t1 join student_enrolment as t2 on t1.degree_program_id = t2.degree_program_id group by t1.degree_program_id order by count(*) desc limit 1

column1: Which student has enrolled for the most times in any program? List the id, first name, middle name, last name, the number of enrollments and student id.
column2: select t1.first_name, t1.middle_name, t1.last_name, count(*), t1.student_id from students as t1 join student_enrolment as t2 on t1.student_id = t2.student_id group by t1.student_id order by count(*) desc limit 1
column3: student_transcripts_tracking | select t1.student_id, t1.first_name, t1.middle_name, t1.last_name, count(*), t1.student_id from students as t1 join student_enrolment as t2 on t1.student_id = t2.student_id group by t1.student_id order by count(*) desc limit 1

column1: What is the first, middle, and last name, along with the id and number of enrollments, for the student who enrolled the most in any program?
column2: select t2.first_name, t2.middle_name, t2.last_name, t1.student_id, count(*) from student_enrolment as t1 join students as t2 on t1.student_id = t2.student_id group by t1.student_id order by count(*) desc limit 1
column3: student_transcripts_tracking | select t1.student_id, t1.first_name, t1.middle_name, t1.last_name, count(*), t1.student_id from students as t1 join student_enrolment as t2 on t1.student_id = t2.student_id group by t1.student_id order by count(*) desc limit 1

column1: Find the last name of the students who currently live in the state of North Carolina but have not registered in any degree program.

column3: student_transcripts_tracking | select t1.last_name from students as t1 join addresses as t2 on t1.current_address_id = t2.address_id where t2.state_province_county = 'NorthCarolina' except select distinct t3.last_name from students as t3 join student_enrolment as t4 on t3.student_id = t4.student_id

column1: What are the last name of the students who live in North Carolina but have not registered in any degree programs?

column1: What is the maximum number of times that a course shows up in different transcripts and what is that course's enrollment id?

column2: select countrycode from countrylanguage where language = "Spanish" group by countrycode order by percentage desc limit 1
column3: world_1 | select countrycode, max(percentage) from countrylanguage where language = "Spanish" group by countrycode

column1: Return the codes of countries for which Spanish is the predominantly spoken language.
column2: select countrycode from countrylanguage where language = "Spanish" group by countrycode having count(*) >= 2
column3: world_1 | select countrycode, max(percentage) from countrylanguage where language = "Spanish" group by countrycode

column1: How many friends does each student have?
column2: select count(*), t1.name from highschooler as t1 join friend as t2 on t1.id = t2.student_id group by t1.id
column3: network_1 | select student_id, count(*) from friend group by student_id

column1: What are the names of the high schoolers and how many friends does each have?
column2: select count(*), t1.name from highschooler as t1 join friend as t2 on t1.id = t2.friend_id group by t1.name
column3: network_1 | select t2.name, count(*) from friend as t1 join highschooler as t2 on t1.student_id = t2.id group by t1.student_id

column1: What is the name of the high schooler who has the greatest number of friends?
column2: select t1.name from highschooler as t1 join friend as t2 on t1.id = t2.friend_id group by t1.id order by count(*) desc limit 1
column3: network_1 | select t2.name from friend as t1 join highschooler as t2 on t1.student_id = t2.id group by t1.student_id order by count(*) desc limit 1

column1: Show the names of high schoolers who have at least 3 friends.
column2: select t1.name from highschooler as t1 join friend as t2 on t1.id = t2.friend_id group by t1.id having count(*) >= 3
column3: network_1 | select t2.name from friend as t1 join highschooler as t2 on t1.student_id = t2.id group by t1.student_id having count(*) >= 3

column1: What are the names of high schoolers who have 3 or more friends?
column2: select t1.name from highschooler as t1 join friend as t2 on t1.id = t2.friend_id group by t1.id having count(*) >= 3
column3: network_1 | select t2.name from friend as t1 join highschooler as t2 on t1.student_id = t2.id group by t1.student_id having count(*) >= 3

column1: Show the names of all of the high schooler Kyle's friends.
column2: select t3.name from highschooler as t1 join friend as t2 on t1.id = t2.friend_id join highschooler as t3 on t1.id = t3.id where t1.name = 'Kyle'
column3: network_1 | select t3.name from friend as t1 join highschooler as t2 on t1.student_id = t2.id join highschooler as t3 on t1.friend_id = t3.id where t2.name = "Kyle"

column1: Return the names of friends of the high school student Kyle.
column2: select t3.name from highschooler as t1 join friend as t2 on t1.id = t2.student_id join likes as t3
column3: network_1 | select t3.name from friend as t1 join highschooler as t2 on t1.student_id = t2.id join highschooler as t3 on t1.friend_id = t3.id where t2.name = "Kyle"

column1: Show the ids of high schoolers who have friends and are also liked by someone else.
column2: select t1.id from highschooler as t1 join friend as t2 on t1.id = t2.student_id intersect select t1.id from highschooler as t1 join likes as t2 on t1.id = t2.student_id
column3: network_1 | select student_id from friend intersect select liked_id from likes

column1: What are the ids of students who both have friends and are liked?
column2: select student_id from friend intersect select student_id from likes
column3: network_1 | select student_id from friend intersect select liked_id from likes

column1: Show name of all students who have some friends and also are liked by someone else.
column2: select t1.name from highschooler as t1 join friend as t2 on t1.id = t2.student_id intersect select t1.name from highschooler as t1 join likes as t2 on t1.id = t2.student_id
column3: network_1 | select t2.name from friend as t1 join highschooler as t2 on t1.student_id = t2.id intersect select t2.name from likes as t1 join highschooler as t2 on t1.liked_id = t2.id

column1: What are the names of high schoolers who both have friends and are liked?
column2: select t1.name from highschooler as t1 join friend as t2 on t1.id = t2.student_id intersect select t1.name from highschooler as t1 join likes as t2 on t1.id = t2.student_id
column3: network_1 | select t2.name from friend as t1 join highschooler as t2 on t1.student_id = t2.id intersect select t2.name from likes as t1 join highschooler as t2 on t1.liked_id = t2.id

column1: What are the names of high schoolers who have a grade of over 5 and have 2 or more friends?
column2: select t1.name from highschooler as t1 join friend as t2 on t1.id = t2.friend_id where t1.grade > 5 group by t1.id having count(*) >= 2
column3: network_1 | select t2.name from friend as t1 join highschooler as t2 on t1.student_id = t2.id where t2.grade > 5 group by t1.student_id having count(*) >= 2

column1: Find the average grade of all students who have some friends.
column2: select avg(t2.grade) from friend as t1 join highschooler as t2 on t1.student_id = t2.id
column3: network_1 | select avg(grade) from highschooler where id in (select t1.student_id from friend as t1 join highschooler as t2 on t1.student_id = t2.id)

column1: What is the average grade of students who have friends?
column2: select avg(grade) from highschooler join friend
column3: network_1 | select avg(grade) from highschooler where id in (select t1.student_id from friend as t1 join highschooler as t2 on t1.student_id = t2.id)

column1: What is the average age of the dogs who have gone through any treatments?
column2: select avg(t2.age) from treatments as t1 join dogs as t2 on t1.dog_id = t2.dog_id
column3: dog_kennels | select avg(age) from dogs where dog_id in ( select dog_id from treatments )

column1: Find the average age of the dogs who went through treatments.
column2: select avg(t2.age) from treatments as t1 join dogs as t2 on t1.dog_id = t2.dog_id
column3: dog_kennels | select avg(age) from dogs where dog_id in ( select dog_id from treatments )

column1: Which professionals live in the state of Indiana or have done treatment on more than 2 treatments? List his or her id, last name and cell phone.
column2: select t2.professional_id, t2.first_name, t2.last_name, t2.cell_number from treatments as t1 join professionals as t2 on t1.professional_id = t2.professional_id where t2.state = "Indiana" group by t2.professional_id having count(*) > 2
column3: dog_kennels | select professional_id, last_name, cell_number from professionals where state = 'Indiana' union select t1.professional_id, t1.last_name, t1.cell_number from professionals as t1 join treatments as t2 on t1.professional_id = t2.professional_id group by t1.professional_id having count(*) > 2

column1: Find the id, last name and cell phone of the professionals who live in the state of Indiana or have performed more than two treatments.
column2: select t1.professional_id, t1.last_name, t1.cell_number from professionals as t1 join treatments as t2 on t1.professional_id = t2.professional_id group by t1.professional_id having t1.state = "Indiana" union select t1.professional_id, t1.last_name, t1.cell_number from professionals as t1 join treatments as t2 on t1.professional_id = t2.professional_id group by t1.professional_id having count(*) > 2
column3: dog_kennels | select professional_id, last_name, cell_number from professionals where state = 'Indiana' union select t1.professional_id, t1.last_name, t1.cell_number from professionals as t1 join treatments as t2 on t1.professional_id = t2.professional_id group by t1.professional_id having count(*) > 2

column1: Which dogs have not cost their owner more than 1000 for treatment ? List the dog names .
column2: select name from dogs where owner_id not in (select dog_id from treatments where cost_of_treatment > 1000)
column3: dog_kennels | select name from dogs where dog_id not in ( select dog_id from treatments group by dog_id having sum(cost_of_treatment) > 1000 )

column1: What are the names of the dogs for which the owner has not spend more than 1000 for treatment ?
column2: select name from dogs where owner_id not in (select dog_id from treatments group by dog_id having sum(cost_of_treatment) > 1000)
column3: dog_kennels | select name from dogs where dog_id not in ( select dog_id from treatments group by dog_id having sum(cost_of_treatment) > 1000 )

column1: Which owner has paid the largest amount of money in total for their dogs? Show the owner id and zip code.
column2: select t1.owner_id, t1.zip_code from owners as t1 join dogs as t2 on t1.owner_id = t2.owner_id group by t1.owner_id order by sum(t2.charge_amount
column3: dog_kennels | select t1.owner_id, t1.zip_code from owners as t1 join dogs as t2 on t1.owner_id = t2.owner_id join treatments as t3 on t2.dog_id = t3.dog_id group by t1.owner_id order by sum(t3.cost_of_treatment) desc limit 1

column1: Find the owner id and zip code of the owner who spent the most money in total for his or her dogs.
column2: select t1.owner_id, t1.zip_code from owners as t1 join dogs as t2 on t1.owner_id = t2.owner_id group by t1.owner_id order by sum(t2.cost_of_treatment
column3: dog_kennels | select t1.owner_id, t1.zip_code from owners as t1 join dogs as t2 on t1.owner_id = t2.owner_id join treatments as t3 on t2.dog_id = t3.dog_id group by t1.owner_id order by sum(t3.cost_of_treatment) desc limit 1

column1: What are the first name and last name of the professionals who have done treatment with cost below average?
column2: select t2.first_name, t2.last_name from treatments as t1 join professionals as t2 on t1.professional_id = t2.professional_id where t1.cost_of_treatment < (select avg(cost_of_treatment) from treatments)
column3: dog_kennels | select distinct t1.first_name, t1.last_name from professionals as t1 join treatments as t2 where cost_of_treatment < ( select avg(cost_of_treatment) from treatments )

column1: Which professionals have operated a treatment that costs less than the average? Give me theor first names and last names.
column2: select t2.first_name, t2.last_name from treatments as t1 join professionals as t2 on t1.professional_id = t2.professional_id where t1.cost_of_treatment < (select avg(cost_of_treatment) from treatments)
column3: dog_kennels | select distinct t1.first_name, t1.last_name from professionals as t1 join treatments as t2 where cost_of_treatment < ( select avg(cost_of_treatment) from treatments )

column1: List pairs of the owner's first name and the dogs's name.
column2: select t1.first_name, t2.name from owners as t1 join dogs as t2 on t1.owner_id = t2.dog_id
column3: dog_kennels | select t1.first_name, t2.name from owners as t1 join dogs as t2 on t1.owner_id = t2.owner_id

column1: List the names of the dogs of the rarest breed and the treatment dates of them.
column2: select t2.name, t1.date_of_treatment from treatments as t1 join dogs as t2 on t1.dog_id = t2.dog_id where t2.breed_code = (select breed_code from breeds order by count(*) desc limit 1)
column3: dog_kennels | select t1.name, t2.date_of_treatment from dogs as t1 join treatments as t2 on t1.dog_id = t2.dog_id where t1.breed_code = ( select breed_code from dogs group by breed_code order by count(*) asc limit 1 )

column1: Which dogs are of the rarest breed? Show their names and treatment dates.
column2: select t2.name, t1.date_of_treatment from treatments as t1 join dogs as t2 on t1.dog_id = t2.dog_id where t2.breed_code = (select breed_code from breeds order by count(*) desc limit 1)
column3: dog_kennels | select t1.name, t2.date_of_treatment from dogs as t1 join treatments as t2 on t1.dog_id = t2.dog_id where t1.breed_code = ( select breed_code from dogs group by breed_code order by count(*) asc limit 1 )

column1: Which dogs are owned by someone who lives in Virginia? List the owner's first name and the dog's name.
column2: select t2.first_name, t2.name from owners as t1 join dogs as t2
column3: dog_kennels | select t1.first_name, t2.name from owners as t1 join dogs as t2 on t1.owner_id = t2.owner_id where t1.state = 'Virginia'

column1: List the last name of the owner owning the youngest dog.
column2: select t1.last_name from owners as t1 join dogs as t2 on t1.owner_id = t2.owner_id order by t2.age asc limit 1
column3: dog_kennels | select t1.last_name from owners as t1 join dogs as t2 on t1.owner_id = t2.owner_id where t2.age = ( select max(age) from dogs )

column1: Who owns the youngest dog? Give me his or her last name.
column2: select t1.last_name from owners as t1 join dogs as t2 on t1.owner_id = t2.owner_id order by t2.age asc limit 1
column3: dog_kennels | select t1.last_name from owners as t1 join dogs as t2 on t1.owner_id = t2.owner_id where t2.age = ( select max(age) from dogs )

column1: How much does the most expensive charge type costs?
column2: select charge_type, sum(charge_amount) from charges order by charge_type desc limit 1
column3: dog_kennels | select max(charge_amount) from charges

column1: Show the property type descriptions of properties belonging to that code.
column2: select t1.property_type_description from ref_property_types as t1 join properties as t2 on t1.property_type_code = t2.property_type_code
column3: real_estate_properties | select t2.property_type_description from properties as t1 join ref_property_types as t2 on t1.property_type_code = t2.property_type_code group by t1.property_type_code
